# General Development Rules

## Project Context

Option seller (theta decay) AI agent for TQQQ/TSLL/NVDL.
Tech stack: Next.js + TailwindCSS (frontend), Python FastAPI (backend), GLM-5 (AI), Longbridge OpenAPI (market data).

## Code Principles

- Keep code concise. No over-engineering, no premature abstraction.
- Write short, clear English comments — explain "why", never "what".
- Every function should do one thing. If it exceeds 40 lines, consider splitting.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Use descriptive variable/function names — the name IS the documentation.

## Before Adding New Features

1. Review the current directory structure and existing implementations.
2. Reuse existing utilities, hooks, services, and components whenever possible.
3. If similar logic exists but can't be directly reused, ASK the user how to handle it before proceeding. Options include: refactoring the original, creating a shared abstraction, or duplicating with justification.
4. Never create a new file for logic that already has a natural home.

## File & Folder Conventions

- Use kebab-case for file names: `option-chain.tsx`, `greeks-calculator.py`
- Group by feature/domain, not by technical role.
- Shared utilities go in `lib/` (frontend) or `core/` (backend).
- Keep imports organized: stdlib → third-party → local, separated by blank lines.

## Error Handling

- Never swallow errors silently. Always log with context.
- Backend: raise typed exceptions with meaningful messages.
- Frontend: show user-friendly error states, log details to console.

## Dependencies

- Always use the latest stable version of any library. Never pin to outdated versions.
- When adding a new dependency, verify the latest stable version first (not alpha/beta/rc).
- Use the package manager to add dependencies (e.g. `npm install`, `pip install`) — do not make up version numbers.

## Git

- Commit messages: imperative mood, concise, lowercase. e.g. `add greeks calculation engine`
- One logical change per commit. Don't mix refactoring with features.
